## History

### Early years (1930s–1990s)

The [Strip](/Las_Vegas_Strip)'s genesis was rather unglamorous, beginning in 1931 with the rather quaintly named [Pair-o-Dice Club](/Pair-O-Dice) on what was then known as [Highway 91](/U.S._Route_91). However, the true harbinger of the modern [Strip](/Las_Vegas_Strip) arrived on April 3, 1941, with the opening of the [El Rancho Vegas](/El_Rancho_Vegas). This establishment, boasting 63 bungalow hotel rooms, holds the distinction of being the first full-service casino-resort on what we now call the [Strip](/Las_Vegas_Strip). Its immediate and undeniable success proved to be a potent catalyst, swiftly leading to the construction of a second nearby hotel, the [Hotel Last Frontier](/Hotel_Last_Frontier), which opened its doors in 1942. [17] [18]

The burgeoning potential of this desert gambling mecca did not escape the notice of less savory characters. Notorious [organized crime](/Organized_crime) figures, most famously [Bugsy Siegel](/Bugsy_Siegel), became deeply invested in the developing [Las Vegas](/Las_Vegas) gaming center. It was mob money, in fact, that largely financed the completion of the [Flamingo](/Flamingo_Las_Vegas), a resort that opened its casino in December 1946, followed by the hotel in March 1947. This set a precedent for the kind of capital that would flow into the area. [Wilbur Clark](/Wilbur_Clark)'s [Desert Inn](/Desert_Inn) resort further solidified this trend, opening its doors in 1950. [19] Interestingly, a significant portion of the funding for many of these early [Las Vegas](/Las_Vegas) ventures was channeled through the [American National Insurance Company](/American_National_Insurance_Company), an entity based in the then-notorious, and rather apt, [gambling empire of Galveston, Texas](/Free_State_of_Galveston). [20] [21] One might say the [Strip](/Las_Vegas_Strip) was built on a foundation of ambition, and quite a lot of questionable cash.

[Las Vegas Boulevard South](/Las_Vegas_Boulevard) itself has undergone several identity changes, previously known as [Hwy 91](/U.S._Route_91), the [Arrowhead Highway](/Arrowhead_Highway), [22] or even the Los Angeles Highway. Its enduring moniker, "The [Strip](/Las_Vegas_Strip)," was bestowed upon it by [Los Angeles police](/Los_Angeles_Police_Department) officer and astute businessman [Guy McAfee](/Guy_McAfee). He drew inspiration from his own hometown's glamorous [Sunset Strip](/Sunset_Strip) in Hollywood, a name that perfectly captured the burgeoning, albeit slightly wilder, allure of [Las Vegas](/Las_Vegas). [23]

• The Strip in late 1940s. Pictured is the gas station of the [Hotel Last Frontier](/Hotel_Last_Frontier), the second hotel on the Strip.

#### Unincorporated town

In 1950, Mayor Ernie Cragin of the [City of Las Vegas](/Las_Vegas) harbored grand ambitions. He sought to annex the entire [Las Vegas Strip](/Las_Vegas_Strip), which, inconveniently for him, lay entirely within the unincorporated territory of [Clark County](/Clark_County,_Nevada). His motivation was clear: to dramatically expand the city's tax base, thereby funding his rather ambitious building agenda and alleviating the city's mounting debt. [24] However, the powerful casino executives, led by [Gus Greenbaum](/Gus_Greenbaum) of the [Flamingo](/Flamingo_Las_Vegas), had other, more self-serving, ideas. They aggressively lobbied the [Clark County](/Clark_County,_Nevada) commissioners, successfully advocating for the area to be granted "town status." [24] This political maneuver resulted in the creation of two distinct [unincorporated towns](/Unincorporated_towns_in_Nevada): [Paradise](/Paradise,_Nevada) and [Winchester](/Winchester,_Nevada). [25] [26] This foresight, or perhaps stubborn self-interest, prevented the [Strip](/Las_Vegas_Strip) from ever truly becoming part of the [City of Las Vegas](/Las_Vegas), a decision that was further solidified more than two decades later when the [Supreme Court of Nevada](/Supreme_Court_of_Nevada) struck down a 1975 state law that would have forcibly absorbed the [Strip](/Las_Vegas_Strip) and other urban areas of [Clark County](/Clark_County,_Nevada) into the city. [27] Sometimes, the best way to stay independent is to simply refuse to be absorbed.

The mid-to-late 20th century saw the continued rise of iconic properties. [Caesars Palace](/Caesars_Palace), a monument to Roman extravagance, was established in 1966. The year 1969 ushered in the era of the true "mega-resort" with the opening of the [International Hotel](/Las_Vegas_Hilton), a colossal structure boasting 1,512 rooms. This property, now known as [Westgate Las Vegas](/Westgate_Las_Vegas), set a new standard for scale and ambition.

The first [MGM Grand Hotel and Casino](/Bally%27s_Las_Vegas) opened its doors in 1973, an even larger behemoth with 2,084 rooms. However, its history is marked by tragedy: on November 21, 1980, the [MGM Grand suffered the worst resort fire](/MGM_Grand_Fire) in the annals of [Las Vegas](/Las_Vegas), a devastating event caused by electrical problems that claimed 87 lives. The resort, a testament to resilience, reopened just eight months later. In 1986, Kirk Kerkorian, the visionary behind the [MGM Grand](/Bally%27s_Las_Vegas), sold the property to [Bally Manufacturing](/Bally_Manufacturing), leading to its renaming as [Bally's](/Bally%27s_Las_Vegas).

### Mega-resorts

The landscape of the [Las Vegas Strip](/Las_Vegas_Strip) underwent a profound transformation with the opening of [The Mirage](/The_Mirage) in 1989. This groundbreaking resort redefined the very essence of the [Las Vegas](/Las_Vegas) experience, signaling a clear shift away from smaller, more intimate hotels and casinos towards grander, more immersive mega-resorts. [28] The 1990s became a decade of explosive growth, witnessing the debut of over 12 new hotels, many of them elaborately themed. Properties like the Egyptian-inspired [Luxor](/Luxor_Las_Vegas), the medieval fantasy of [Excalibur](/Excalibur_Hotel_and_Casino), and the tropical elegance of [Mandalay Bay](/Mandalay_Bay) captivated visitors with their fantastical narratives. This era also saw the construction of [The Bellagio](/Bellagio_(resort)), which, at a staggering $1.7 billion, held the title of the world's most expensive hotel at the time. [29] A pivotal moment in the evolution of [Strip](/Las_Vegas_Strip) entertainment arrived in 1993 with the launch of the [Mystère](/Myst%C3%A8re_(Cirque_du_Soleil)) show by [Cirque du Soleil](/Cirque_du_Soleil) at the newly opened [Treasure Island](/Treasure_Island_Hotel_and_Casino) hotel. [19] This marked a significant pivot towards sophisticated, non-gaming entertainment as a core attraction.

In a somewhat misguided attempt to broaden its appeal, resorts during this period also began to offer more attractions explicitly geared towards families and younger audiences. These efforts, while well-intentioned, met with rather limited success. [30] The core demographic, it seemed, was less interested in sanitized fun and more in the allure of adult escapism. The current [MGM Grand](/MGM_Grand_Las_Vegas), a truly massive complex, opened its doors in 1993, further cementing the trend of monumental scale. [31]

Beyond the colossal hotels, casinos, and resorts, the [Strip](/Las_Vegas_Strip) had already begun to diversify its offerings with numerous standalone attractions. These included the saccharine delights of [M&M's World](/M%26M%27s_World), the indoor thrills of [Adventuredome](/Adventuredome), and the extensive retail therapy available at the [Fashion Show Mall](/Fashion_Show_Mall). Even the [Nevada National Guard](/Nevada_National_Guard) has found a role, assisting with the inevitable security challenges posed by New Year's Eve revelries.

### 2000–present

The turn of the millennium saw the [Strip](/Las_Vegas_Strip) pivot once more, this time towards an even more refined, luxurious, and high-end segment. This trend was unmistakably signaled by the openings of the opulent [Bellagio](/Bellagio_(resort_and_casino)) (1998), the Italianate splendor of [The Venetian](/The_Venetian,_Las_Vegas) (1999), and the sophisticated elegance of the [Wynn](/Wynn_Las_Vegas) (2005), [The Palazzo](/The_Palazzo) (2007), and [Encore](/Encore_Las_Vegas) (2008). During this period, many older resorts undertook significant expansions and renovations, often accompanied by a "de-theming" process, shedding some of the more overt, kitschy narratives of the previous decade in favor of a more contemporary, upscale aesthetic. [32] [33]

A truly ambitious undertaking, [CityCenter](/CityCenter), was announced in 2004 and subsequently constructed between 2006 and 2009. This colossal 66-acre (27-hectare) multi-use project, costing an eye-watering $8.5 billion (in 2009 [USD](/United_States_dollar), an amount equivalent to approximately $16.1 billion in March 2025), rose from the former site of the [Boardwalk](/Boardwalk_Hotel_and_Casino) hotel and adjacent land. Most of its constituent elements, a testament to rapid development, opened their doors in late 2009. [34]

• Four-segment panorama of The Cosmopolitan, Bellagio, and Caesars Palace (left to right) from the Las Vegas Strip, across from the Bellagio fountains

The pursuit of non-gaming attractions continued in 2012 with the groundbreaking for the [High Roller Ferris wheel](/High_Roller_(Ferris_wheel)) and an accompanying retail district, [The Linq Promenade](/The_Linq_Promenade). These developments aimed to further diversify the entertainment landscape beyond the traditional casino resort model. The ongoing transformation of the [Strip](/Las_Vegas_Strip) continued in 2014 with significant renovations and rebrandings, including [The Cromwell Las Vegas](/The_Cromwell_Las_Vegas) and the [SLS Las Vegas](/SLS_Las_Vegas). In 2015, the [Las Vegas Festival Grounds](/Las_Vegas_Festival_Grounds) opened, providing a dedicated space for large-scale events. The year 2016 saw further additions to the entertainment infrastructure with the opening of [T-Mobile Arena](/T-Mobile_Arena), [35] The Park, and the [Park Theater](/Dolby_Live) (now known as [Dolby Live](/Dolby_Live)).

However, the [Strip](/Las_Vegas_Strip)'s narrative is not without its shadows. On October 1, 2017, a lone [gunman](/Stephan_Paddock) positioned within the [Mandalay Bay](/Mandalay_Bay) hotel tragically [opened fire](/2017_Las_Vegas_shooting) on a nearby concert, resulting in 60 fatalities and the gunman's own death. This horrific event remains the [deadliest mass shooting in U.S. history](/Mass_shootings_in_the_United_States).

• The Las Vegas Strip as viewed from the [Strat](/The_Strat) Observation Deck, 2025

The 2020s have continued this dynamic evolution. In 2021, the [Pinball Hall of Fame](/Pinball_Hall_of_Fame) relocated to a new, prominent spot near the iconic "Fabulous Las Vegas" sign at the [Strip](/Las_Vegas_Strip)'s southern end. [36] Later that year, [Resorts World Las Vegas](/Resorts_World_Las_Vegas) made its grand debut in June, rising majestically from the hallowed grounds of the former [Stardust Resort and Casino](/Stardust_Resort_and_Casino). [37]

The architectural marvel that is the [Sphere](/Sphere_(venue)) opened its doors in September 2023, instantly becoming a globally recognized landmark. [38] That same year, in December, the [Fontainebleau Las Vegas](/Fontainebleau_Las_Vegas) finally opened, occupying the sites of the former [El Rancho Hotel and Casino](/El_Rancho_Hotel_and_Casino) and [Algiers Hotel](/Algiers_Hotel) after years of anticipation. [39] The retail landscape also saw expansion with [BLVD](/Blvd_(Las_Vegas)), a three-story shopping center, which opened in November 2024, with additional tenants slated to debut through 2026. [40]

### Future developments

The [Las Vegas Strip](/Las_Vegas_Strip) is a perpetual construction site, always looking to its next iteration. The [Tropicana](/Tropicana_Las_Vegas), a venerable institution, was ceremoniously demolished in October 2024. Its footprint will be transformed into the site of a new [Bally's Las Vegas](/Bally%27s_Las_Vegas_(new_resort)) resort [41] and the ambitious [New Las Vegas Stadium](/New_Las_Vegas_Stadium). This stadium is destined to become the permanent home of [the Athletics](/Athletics_(baseball)) once they complete their relocation to [Las Vegas](/Las_Vegas) from their [temporary home](/Sutter_Health_Park) in [Sacramento](/West_Sacramento,_California). [42] [43] Both the stadium and the new hotel are projected to open in 2028, coinciding with the 2028 MLB season. [44] Not to be outdone, [The Mirage](/The_Mirage) also closed its doors in July 2024, but its legacy will endure as it prepares to reopen as the [Hard Rock Las Vegas](/Hard_Rock_Las_Vegas) in 2027. [45] The only constant, it seems, is change, and the persistent hum of construction.

## Transportation

Navigating the vibrant, often overwhelming, expanse of the [Las Vegas Strip](/Las_Vegas_Strip) is an experience in itself, with a variety of transportation options catering to every level of urgency and preferred level of glamour.

### Buses

[RTC Transit](/RTC_Transit), formerly known by the rather less catchy moniker of Citizens Area Transit (CAT), provides comprehensive bus service along the [Strip](/Las_Vegas_Strip). Their distinctive [double decker buses](/Double_decker_bus), affectionately known as [The Deuce](/The_Deuce_(transit_bus_service)), are a familiar sight. [46] These buses traverse the entire length of the [Strip](/Las_Vegas_Strip), connecting the iconic "Welcome to Fabulous Las Vegas" sign and the South Strip Transfer Terminal to the Bonneville Transit Center (BTC) and the lively [Fremont Street Experience](/Fremont_Street_Experience) in [Downtown Las Vegas](/Downtown_Las_Vegas). Convenient stops are strategically located near virtually every major casino, ensuring that a ride is never far off.

### Trams

For those seeking a more exclusive, and often complimentary, mode of transport, several free trams operate along the west side of the [Strip](/Las_Vegas_Strip), connecting various properties with effortless grace. [47] These include:

*   The [Mandalay Bay Tram](/Mandalay_Bay_Tram), which seamlessly links the [Mandalay Bay Resort and Casino](/Mandalay_Bay_Resort_and_Casino), [Luxor Hotel](/Luxor_Hotel), and [Excalibur Hotel and Casino](/Excalibur_Hotel_and_Casino).
*   The [Aria Express](/Aria_Express), connecting [Park MGM](/Park_MGM), [Crystals](/The_Crystals_(Las_Vegas)) (which also serves as a stop for [Aria Resort and Casino](/Aria_Resort_and_Casino)), and the [Bellagio](/Bellagio_(resort_and_casino)).
*   The [Hard Rock-Treasure Island Tram](/Hard_Rock-Treasure_Island_Tram), which, when operational, runs between [Treasure Island](/Treasure_Island_Hotel_and_Casino) and the [Hard Rock Las Vegas](/Hard_Rock_Las_Vegas). (Currently, it remains temporarily closed, a minor inconvenience in the grand scheme of things.)

