### Monorail

While not directly on the [Strip](/Las_Vegas_Strip) itself, the [Las Vegas Monorail](/Las_Vegas_Monorail) offers a rapid and efficient alternative for traversing the eastern side of the [Strip](/Las_Vegas_Strip) corridor. Its 3.9-mile route extends from Tropicana Avenue to [Sahara Avenue](/Sahara_Avenue), with trains arriving every 4 to 8 minutes. [48] [49] It provides convenient access to several on-Strip properties, with the [MGM Grand](/MGM_Grand_Las_Vegas) and [The Sahara](/Sahara_Las_Vegas) anchoring each end of its route. [49] The stations, a testament to strategic placement, include:

*   [SAHARA](/Sahara_Las_Vegas) Las Vegas Station
*   [Westgate](/Westgate_Las_Vegas) Station
*   [Las Vegas Convention Center](/Las_Vegas_Convention_Center) Station
*   [Harrah's](/Harrah%27s_Las_Vegas)/[The LINQ](/The_Linq) Station
*   [Flamingo](/Flamingo_Las_Vegas)/[Caesars Palace](/Caesars_Palace) Station
*   [Horseshoe](/Horseshoe_Las_Vegas)/[Paris](/Paris_Las_Vegas) Station
*   [MGM Grand](/MGM_Grand_Las_Vegas) Station

The monorail's journey began modestly in 1995, utilizing two trains originally sourced from [Walt Disney World](/Walt_Disney_World). [50] In 2020, recognizing its vital role in the city's infrastructure, the monorail system was acquired by the [Las Vegas Convention and Visitors Authority](/Las_Vegas_Convention_and_Visitors_Authority) (LVCVA). [51]

