### Demolished or closed Strip casinos and hotels

The history of the [Las Vegas Strip](/Las_Vegas_Strip) is as much about what has been torn down as what has been built. A truly remarkable number of casinos and hotels have, over the decades, ceased operations, only to be replaced by newer, grander, or simply different visions. A partial necrology of these fallen giants includes:

*   [Aladdin](/Aladdin_(hotel_and_casino)): This property had a rather convoluted identity, initially opening in 1962 as the Tallyho. It briefly became the King's Crown Tallyho in 1963 before settling on the name [Aladdin](/Aladdin_(hotel_and_casino)) in 1966. It was ultimately demolished in 1998, only for a new [Aladdin](/Aladdin_(hotel_and_casino)) resort to rise on the same site in 2000, which was then rebranded as [Planet Hollywood](/Planet_Hollywood_Resort_%26_Casino) in 2007. A phoenix, but with more glitter.
*   Big Red's Casino: A fleeting presence, it opened in 1981 and closed just a year later in 1982. The property was later developed for CBS Sports World Casino in 1997, a name that swiftly changed to Sports World Casino after [CBS](/CBS) rather predictably threatened legal action. [96] It too closed in 2001 and is now, rather mundanely, a shopping center.
*   [Barbary Coast](/Barbary_Coast_Hotel_and_Casino): Opened in 1978, it closed in 2007 and was subsequently known as Bill's Gamblin' Hall until 2010. Today, it has been reborn as [The Cromwell](/The_Cromwell).
*   [Boardwalk Hotel and Casino](/Boardwalk_Hotel_and_Casino): This property ceased operations on January 9, 2006, and was spectacularly demolished on May 9, 2006, clearing the way for the ambitious [CityCenter](/CityCenter) development.
*   [Castaways](/Castaways_(casino)): Originally known as the Sans Souci Hotel when it opened in 1955, it became the [Castaways](/Castaways_(casino)) in 1963 and was demolished in 1987. Its former site is now occupied by [The Mirage](/The_Mirage).
*   [Desert Inn](/Desert_Inn): A grand dame of the [Strip](/Las_Vegas_Strip), it closed on August 28, 2000, and was demolished between 2001 and 2004. Its legacy lives on as the site of [Wynn Las Vegas](/Wynn_Las_Vegas) and [Encore Las Vegas](/Encore_Las_Vegas), though its renowned golf course was not only retained but significantly improved.
*   [Dunes](/Dunes_(hotel_and_casino)): This iconic resort closed on January 26, 1993, and was demolished in a series of spectacular implosions between 1993 and 1994. Its extensive footprint is now home to parts of [Park MGM](/Park_MGM), [CityCenter](/CityCenter), and [T-Mobile Arena](/T-Mobile_Arena).
*   [El Rancho (formerly Thunderbird/Silverbird)](/El_Rancho_Hotel_and_Casino): Closed in 1992 and demolished in 2000. Its former grounds are now occupied by the majestic [Fontainebleau Las Vegas](/Fontainebleau_Las_Vegas).
*   [El Rancho Vegas](/El_Rancho_Vegas): The trailblazer, it tragically burned down in 1960. A portion of its southern edge is now home to the [Hilton Grand Vacations Club](/Hilton_Grand_Vacations_Club) timeshare, while the remainder of the site has been transformed into the [Las Vegas Festival Grounds](/Las_Vegas_Festival_Grounds).
*   [Hacienda](/Hacienda_(Las_Vegas)): Closed and demolished in December 1996, its site is now occupied by [Mandalay Bay](/Mandalay_Bay). (A separate [Hacienda](/Hoover_Dam_Lodge) operated outside [Boulder City](/Boulder_City) until 2015, formerly known as the [Gold Strike Inn](/Hoover_Dam_Lodge), adding to the confusion.)
*   [Holy Cow Casino and Brewery](/Holy_Cow_Casino_and_Brewery): Notable as the first microbrewery in [Las Vegas](/Las_Vegas). It closed in 2002 and is now, rather disappointingly, a [Walgreens](/Walgreens) store.
*   Jackpot Casino: Closed in 1977, its property is now integrated into the sprawling [Bonanza Gift Shop](/Bonanza_Gift_Shop).
*   [Klondike Hotel and Casino](/Klondike_Hotel_and_Casino): This property closed in 2006 and was demolished in 2008.
*   Little Caesars Casino: Operated from 1970 to 1994. [Paris Las Vegas](/Paris_Las_Vegas) now occupies the area where it once stood. [97]
*   Money Tree Casino: Closed in 1979, its site is also now part of the [Bonanza Gift Shop](/Bonanza_Gift_Shop).
*   [Marina Hotel and Casino](/Marina_Hotel_and_Casino): Upon its closure, it was ingeniously adapted and integrated into the original [MGM Grand](/MGM_Grand_Las_Vegas), now forming the West Wing of the current [MGM Grand Las Vegas](/MGM_Grand_Las_Vegas).
*   [Mirage](/The_Mirage): This iconic resort officially closed on July 17, 2024, and is slated to reopen as a [Hard Rock](/Hard_Rock_Las_Vegas) resort in 2027. [45]
*   [New Frontier](/New_Frontier_Hotel_and_Casino): Closed on July 16, 2007, and was dramatically demolished on November 13, 2007.
*   [Nob Hill Casino](/Casino_Royale_Hotel_%26_Casino): Opened in 1979 and closed in 1990. [98] Its former location is now occupied by [Casino Royale](/Casino_Royale_Hotel_%26_Casino).
*   [Riviera Hotel and Casino](/Riviera_(hotel_and_casino)): Opened in 1955, it closed its doors in May 2015 to make way for the ambitious [Las Vegas Global Business District](/Las_Vegas_Global_Business_District).
*   [Royal Nevada](/Royal_Nevada): Opened in 1955, it was subsequently absorbed into the [Stardust](/Stardust_Resort_and_Casino) in 1959.
*   [Sands Hotel and Casino](/Sands_Hotel_and_Casino): This legendary establishment closed on June 30, 1996, and was demolished later that year. Its site is now home to [The Venetian](/The_Venetian_Las_Vegas).
*   [Silver City Casino](/Silver_City_Casino): Closed in 1999, its former location is now the Silver City Plaza Shopping Center.
*   [Silver Slipper](/Silver_Slipper_(Las_Vegas)) Casino: Opened in 1950, it closed and was demolished in 1988. Its site then served as a parking lot for the [New Frontier](/New_Frontier_Hotel_and_Casino) until that resort's closure and demolition in 2007.
*   [Stardust Resort and Casino](/Stardust_Resort_and_Casino): Closed on November 1, 2006, and was spectacularly demolished on March 13, 2007. Its hallowed ground is now occupied by [Resorts World](/Resorts_World_Las_Vegas).
*   [Tropicana Las Vegas](/Tropicana_Las_Vegas): This venerable icon closed on April 2, 2024, and was brought down by [implosion](/Building_implosion) on October 9, 2024. It is set to be replaced by the [New Las Vegas Stadium](/New_Las_Vegas_Stadium), which will become the future home of the [Las Vegas Athletics](/Oakland_Athletics). [99]
*   [Vegas World](/Vegas_World): Opened in 1979 and closed in 1995. Its site is now home to [The Strat](/The_Strat_(Las_Vegas)).
*   [Westward Ho Hotel and Casino](/Westward_Ho_Hotel_and_Casino): Closed in 2005 and demolished in 2006. Its former location is now, ironically, a [McDonald's](/McDonald%27s). [100]

